text: Oh! One more example! In Don't You Forget About Me – the bridge after the first chorus happens only that one time. How? Ugh. But it works.
OK. I've said my bit. Hit me up with your favorite non-continuity-conserving songs.
The Beatles – You Never Give Me Your Money, Prefab Sprout – Moving the River, Billy Joel – Where's the Orchestra?
I'm gonna sound like a snob but my favorite songs are becoming ones that don't have continuity. And not purposely, like Bohemian Rhapsody.
Another is the riff (intro, then brought back ONCE in the outro) in Rage Against the Machine's Killing In The Name.
A perfect non-Beatle example of all this: "And the most she will do is throw shadows at you…" part in Billy Joel's She's Always A Woman.
But for a shmo like me, I feel like I don't have the clout for anyone to trust that my small deviations are worthwhile.
Every little change adds complexity. We accept it when The Beatles do it – it's part of what makes them "special." We're familiar with them.
The reason this is frustrating is, I think of music as existing on the page – I try to write simple songs you could play at a campfire…
The worst offense that drives me crazy is that in She Loves You, the C in the intro is major. The rest of the song? Every C is a C minor.
Outros: Please Please Me and Yes It Is and Help!. Intros: I've Just Seen A Face and Strawberry Fields Forever. Bridges: No Reply.
And yet it all sounds natural, it fits; we don't need those parts to repeat. Other examples: intros to Here, There, & Everywhere/If I Fell.
But they did this ALL the time. Look at the atypical structure of Martha My Dear. That bridge happens once – "Take a go0od look around you."
Some are obvious: piano riff into in While My Guitar Gently Weeps, huge chord at the top of A Hard Day's Night, I Feel Fine feedback.
But what I think most people try to quantify as The Beatle's "brilliance" comes down to the subtle, daring shifts they made in their songs.
Can't Buy Me Love, We Can Work It Out, Nowhere Man, Get Back, I've Got A Feeling… the list goes on and on and on.
This is what makes studying The Beatles so frustrating. They had a ton of songs that had continuity throughout; every musical idea repeated.
The most frustrating part of being a songwriter, for me, is trusting that I've got a strong, self contained intro, bridge, or outro.
